# Building a Single Node OpenShift Lab: VM Configuration & Troubleshooting on Fedora

Deploying a Single Node OpenShift (SNO) cluster locally via KVM/QEMU requires exact virtual machine configurations to prevent silent failures and resource starvation. 

This guide covers the end-to-end setup: bootstrapping the cluster via Red Hat's Assisted Installer, executing the critical VM XML edits needed for OpenShift CoreOS (RHCOS) to run smoothly on a Fedora host, and configuring local DNS.

---

## 1. Generating the Discovery ISO

The most reliable way to deploy a KVM-based SNO cluster is using the Red Hat Hybrid Cloud Console.

1.  Navigate to [cloud.redhat.com](https://cloud.redhat.com) and log in.
2.  Go to **OpenShift > Clusters > Create Cluster**.
![alt text](image.png)
3.  Select the **Datacenter** tab and on **Assisted Installer** click on **create clsuter**.
4.  Configure the initial cluster details:
    *   **Cluster Name:** `local-sno` (or your preferred name).
    *   **Base Domain:** `example.com` (or your preferred domain).
    *   **Install single node OpenShift (SNO):** Ensure this box is checked.
![alt text](image-1.png)
5.  Click next and select any operators you want, I am skipping any additional operators right now as I wont have enough ram for my setup.

6. Click next and in host discovery tab select **add a host**. Select **Full image file** as I have noticed its the most stable for these kinds of setups
**Inject your SSH Key:** During the wizard configuration, ensure you paste your host machine's public SSH key (usually `~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub`). If you skip this, you will be permanently locked out of the `core` user backend later.
If you dont have a key generated then you can run the following command on the host machine
    ```bash
    ssh-keygen
    ```
    ![alt text](image-2.png)

7.  Generate the **Discovery ISO**. You will mount this ISO to your virtual machine so it can boot and register itself with the Red Hat console.

> If the downloaded file is exactly 1024 MB then the fiel downloaded might be currupted, make sure to use any kind of download manager as usually no openshift image is exactly 1024 MB

8. If your download speed is super slow then I suggest using a download manager like free download manager [freedownloadmanager.org](https://www.freedownloadmanager.org/)
and copy the **Discovery ISO URL** to the download manager for a faster speed.
![alt text](image-4.png)

